 The most important change is the fact that no part of the setup is now
 pumped by roughing pump.
 All tubing that needs to be regularly evacuated are now connected to a
 buffer volume which is in turn pumped by a turbo-pump through a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{4}"$
\end_inset

 pipe.
 The role of the buffer volume is to provide a large volume to absorb burst
 of gas to before they reach the turbo pump.
 This is especially important when you put a turbo pump at the vacuum side
 of a pressure controller since these devices will typically undershoot
 quite a bit when they go down in pressure.
 If the turbo pump is attached directly to the pressure controller these
 undershoots will be extremely hard on the turbo, thus the buffer volume
 purpose with life is to smoothen out these burst to make them tolerable
 for the turbo.
 The system works beautifuly and makes it possible to pump down the entire
 system to approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}\,$
\end_inset

mbar with absolutely no oil in the residual gas.
 Even though this is of course not real UHV it is still a background pressure
 approximately 8 orders of magnitude below the typical operating pressure
 of the setup.
 A small drawback on the new design is that all for the main gas-flow must
 go through the turbo-pump thus somewhat limiting the total acceptable flow,
 thus increasing the time needed to achieve a stable flow of a given gas-mixture.
 This problem is not too servery, however, experimentation has shown that
 we go as high as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10\,$
\end_inset

mL/min without drawing excessive currents in the turbo, this flow is high
 enough for most purposes, and certainly high enough that pressure measurement
 of the reactor becomes unreliable due to flow resistance in the main outlet,
 thus we typically try to stay well below 
\begin_inset Formula $10\,$
\end_inset

mL/min anyway.
